Residuals of the MLP models were bootstrapped 200 times based on HMM. The HMM bootstrapping allowed the collection of a distributional profile of w for the most accurate prediction of the network efficiency scores and competition indexes. The stochastic HMM used in this research enables the assessment of endogeneity between efficiency and competitiveness variables by means of the respective transition probabilities for each state. Consider that there are j observations for each bank X at time t that are given as {Xtj: t = 1, …, T; j = 1,…, J}. Also assume that these random vectors are mutually independent. The HMM is structured upon choosing a proper distributional assumption of the random vectors Xtj at each one of the m states of the HMM. Therefore, transition probabilities should be determined for t = 1, 2, …, T, i = 1, 2, …, m, and for all relevant xtj, like in Wanke, dos Henrique et al. (2019), Wanke et al. (2019), Wanke et al. (2019)). Here, the stochastic HMM is modelled as a multinomial distribution for each bank j at each state i over time t. The likelihood function is given as (Zucchini et al., 2016):22PXtj=diagP1Xtj,…,PmXtj\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
